.TH FACTOR(1),User Commands,FACTOR(1)

.SH NAME
factor - print the prime factorization of a number

.SH SYNOPSIS
factor number

.SH DESCRIPTION
factor prints number followed by a colon and each of its prime factors separated by spaces.
Repeated prime factors are printed once per occurrence.

number is parsed as a 32-bit integer.
It may be given in decimal, or in hexadecimal when prefixed with $ or 0x.

Factors below 2 produce no factorization: the number is printed followed by the colon and a newline.

Trial division is used, so the time to factor a number grows with the square root of its largest prime factor.

.SH EXAMPLES
$ factor 60

 60: 2 2 3 5

$ factor 4294967291

 4294967291: 4294967291

$ factor 0xFF

 255: 3 5 17

.SH EXIT STATUS
0: Factorization printed successfully.

1: No number was given, or the argument could not be parsed as a number.
